"african-elephant":{n:"African Elephant",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Grey",i:"ğŸ˜",wp:"African_bush_elephant",d:"Addo was established in 1931 to protect the last 11 elephants. Today over 600 roam the park. They consume 200-300 kg of plants daily. The park's elephants are known for being relaxed around vehicles.",w:"Up to 6,000 kg",l:"3-4 m shoulder",life:"60-70 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, bark, roots, fruit",cs:"Endangered"},
"lion":{n:"Lion",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Large",cl:"Tawny",i:"ğŸ¦",wp:"Lion",d:"Reintroduced in 2003 after 100+ year absence. Around 17 in the main area. Most active at night and early morning. Their return changed buffalo and prey species behaviour significantly.",w:"150-250 kg",l:"1.7-2.5 m",life:"10-14 years",act:"Mostly nocturnal",diet:"Carnivore â€” buffalo, zebra, antelope",cs:"Vulnerable"},
"leopard":{n:"Leopard",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Large",cl:"Spotted",i:"ğŸ†",wp:"African_leopard",d:"Present throughout the expanded park but extremely elusive. Solitary nocturnal hunters preferring thick bush. They cache kills in trees to protect from other predators. Seeing one at Addo is a rare privilege.",w:"60-90 kg",l:"1-1.9 m",life:"12-17 years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Carnivore â€” antelope, hyrax, birds",cs:"Vulnerable"},
"black-rhinoceros":{n:"Black Rhinoceros",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Grey",i:"ğŸ¦",wp:"Black_rhinoceros",d:"Over 48 critically endangered south-western black rhinos live here. Solitary browsers that rest in thick bush by day. Their hooked upper lip is designed for grasping branches. Addo's dense thicket provides excellent cover for them.",w:"800-1,400 kg",l:"3-3.75 m",life:"35-50 years",act:"Nocturnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Browser â€” shrubs, bushes, herbs",cs:"Critically Endangered"},
"cape-buffalo":{n:"Cape Buffalo",c:"Mammal",s:"Big 5",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Dark Brown",i:"ğŸ¦¬",wp:"African_buffalo",d:"Over 400 disease-free buffalo roam Addo. Since lion reintroduction they form tighter herds and are seen more during daylight. Old bulls can be aggressive. Look for cattle egrets perched on their backs.",w:"500-900 kg",l:"1.7-3.4 m",life:"15-25 years",act:"Day & night",diet:"Grazer â€” grasses",cs:"Near Threatened"},
